 Giles Hammond asked this question · 16 karma · Dec 18 at 05:48 AM

I have a repository on BitBucket, created by importing the public Sparkle for OSX project from Github.

If I try to clone this to my local machine with Sourcetree everything works fine:
{code}git -c diff.mnemonicprefix=false -c core.quotepath=false -c credential.helper=sourcetree clone --recursive https://MyUsername@bitbucket.org/MyUsername/sparkle.git /Users/Giles/Dropbox/Projects/sparkle{code}

However, if I try and do the same to a submodule within an existing project it fails with a password issue:

{code}git -c diff.mnemonicprefix=false -c core.quotepath=false -c credential.helper=sourcetree submodule add -f https://MyUsername@bitbucket.org/MyUsername/sparkle.git External/Sparkle
 
fatal: could not read Password for 'https://MyUsername@bitbucket.org': Device not configured{code}
Does anyone know if I am doing something very wrong here? I am fairly new to Git, Sourcetree and Bitbucket. Perhaps this is a bug though - the password is obviously working when cloning in some instances.
Thank you 
{quote}

(Related AAC: https://answers.atlassian.com/questions/244606/sourcetree-fails-on-password-when-cloning-to-submodule)

When you remove a GIT sub module it only get removed from *.gitmodules* however that just the start.

How to reproduce it:
* Create a git project and add another git remote project as submodule.
* Delete the sub project

Actual:
* Only *.gitmodules* is updated.

Expected:
* Delete the relevant section from the .gitmodules file. (/)
{code}
    [submodule "vendor"]
    	path = vendor
    	url = git://github.com/some-user/some-repo.git
{code}

* Delete the relevant section from .git/config. (x)
{code}
    [submodule "vendor"]
    	url = git://github.com/some-user/some-repo.git
{code}
* Remove Submodule cache (x)
{code}
git rm --cached path/to/submodule
# Don't include a trailing slash -- that will lead to an error.
{code}
* Remove Submodule meta data (x)
{code}
rm -rf .git/modules/submodule_name
{code}
* Remove untracked submodule files  (x)
{code}
rm -rf path/to/submodule
{code}

